    <h2>Types of Child Custody in Maryland</h2>

    <h3>Legal Custody</h3>
    <p>
      Legal custody refers to the right and responsibility to make major decisions about a child's life — including decisions about education, healthcare, religious upbringing, and extracurricular activities.
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Sole Legal Custody:</strong> One parent has the exclusive right to make major decisions for the child. This is appropriate when the parents are unable to cooperate, or when one parent has a history of abuse, neglect, or unavailability.</li>
      <li><strong>Joint Legal Custody:</strong> Both parents share the right and responsibility to make major decisions for the child. This requires a baseline of communication and cooperation between the parents. Joint legal custody is common in Maryland when both parents are actively involved in the child's life.</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>Physical Custody</h3>
    <p>
      Physical custody refers to where the child lives and which parent has day-to-day care and control.
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Sole (Primary) Physical Custody:</strong> The child lives primarily with one parent, who is the "custodial parent," while the other parent typically receives scheduled visitation (access).</li>
      <li><strong>Shared/Joint Physical Custody:</strong> The child divides significant parenting time between both parents. This does not necessarily mean 50/50 — it means the child has substantial regular time with both parents.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>The Best Interests of the Child Standard</h2>
    <p>
      In every Maryland custody determination, the governing legal standard is the <strong>best interests of the child</strong>. Maryland courts evaluate a wide range of factors in making this determination, including:
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li>The fitness and character of each parent</li>
      <li>The child's relationship with each parent</li>
      <li>The material opportunities available to the child with each parent</li>
      <li>The age, health, and gender of the child</li>
      <li>The length of separation from each parent</li>
      <li>Any prior abandonment or surrender of custody</li>
      <li>The child's preference (considered at appropriate age and maturity)</li>
      <li>The opportunity for the child to maintain sibling relationships</li>
      <li>Each parent's ability to support the child's relationship with the other parent</li>
      <li>Any history of domestic violence or abuse</li>
    </ul>
    <p>
      Our attorneys build compelling, evidence-based cases documenting your parental fitness, your involvement in your child's life, and why your proposed custody arrangement best serves your child's interests.
    </p>

    <h2>Parenting Plans in Maryland</h2>
    <p>
      A comprehensive parenting plan is the foundation of every effective custody arrangement. A well-crafted parenting plan addresses:
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li>Regular weekly and weekend schedule</li>
      <li>Holiday and vacation schedule</li>
      <li>School year vs. summer schedule</li>
      <li>Decision-making processes for education, healthcare, and religion</li>
      <li>Transportation arrangements and exchanges</li>
      <li>Communication protocols between co-parents</li>
      <li>Relocation restrictions and procedures</li>
      <li>Dispute resolution mechanisms</li>
    </ul>
    <p>
      Our attorneys draft detailed, child-centered parenting plans that anticipate future conflicts and provide clear guidance — minimizing the need for future court intervention.
    </p>

    <h2>Contested Custody Cases</h2>
    <p>
      When parents cannot agree on a custody arrangement, the matter is decided by a Maryland Circuit Court judge after an evidentiary hearing or trial. Contested custody cases are our specialty. We prepare meticulously — gathering witness testimony, documentation of parental involvement, expert opinions, and comprehensive evidence — to present the most compelling case possible.
    </p>

    <h2>Child Custody During Divorce</h2>
    <p>
      Child custody is typically addressed alongside the divorce proceeding itself. Our attorneys coordinate custody strategy with all other divorce-related matters — ensuring that positions taken on custody align with and support positions on child support, property division, and other key issues.
    </p>

    <h2>50/50 Custody in Maryland</h2>
    <p>
      Maryland courts do not automatically favor 50/50 (equal shared) custody — but they will award it when the evidence shows it serves the child's best interests and both parents are capable, committed, and able to cooperate. Our attorneys build strong cases for equal shared custody arrangements when appropriate and advise on realistic expectations when equal time may not serve the child best.
    </p>

